<HEADLINE>
<P>
BESTER STOPS 45 SHOTS IN LEADING TORONTO OVER ST. LOUIS, 6-3 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TORONTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Goaltender Alan Bester made a triumphant return from the minors to lead the 
Toronto Maple Leafs to a 6-3 victory over the St. Louis Blues Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
Tom Kurvers, Lou Franceschetti, Mark Osborne, Al Iafrate, John Kordic and 
Wendel Clark scored for Toronto, which won for the fifth time in its last six 
games to move into a tie for third in the Norris Division with the Blues. 
</P>
<P>
Bester, making his first start for the Maple Leafs since being recalled from 
Newmarket after a self-imposed two-week conditioning stint, stopped 45 shots. 
</P>
<P>
The Maple Leafs took 25 shots on St. Louis goalie Pat Jablonski. 
</P>
<P>
Clark opened the scoring on a rebound of a Daniel Marois shot for his 11th of 
the season at 18:46. 
</P>
<P>
The Maple Leafs blew the game open with four goals in the second period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
