<P>
View; Part E; Page 16; Column 1; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
450 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: FANTASY CURBS, DISPLACES RAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: I often have problems in relationships because of my short 
fuse. I get angry, have an outburst of rage and say things I regret. As a 
result, the person walks out, never to return, and most of the time, I suffer 
from loneliness. My sister tells me that she has the same kind of temper but 
when she's angry she works through it in her imagination. Is this crazy? -- 
G.U. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR G.U.: I don't think so. It's not a bad idea to fantasize about what you 
would do if you could, and then let it go. Some people have told me that when 
someone cuts them off in traffic or is otherwise rude and unfriendly, they 
fantasize whipping out their make-believe revolver and shooting out the 
person's tires. This harmless dream relieves their rage. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ned Marcus, a psychiatrist, points out that dreams are a way of releasing 
suppressed anger. Freud believed that dreams are a safety valve through which 
our mean, dark, horrid impulses could escape harmlessly. 
</P>
<P>
Fantasies never hurt anybody. You are allowed to dream about or think of almost 
anything you wish, and unless you act upon the dream, there's no reason to feel 
guilty. 
</P>
<P>
Once you learn to handle your anger, you'll probably find that you are less 
lonely and that your relationships are vastly improved. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: Should a 6-year-old be severely punished for lying? My 
husband believes they should be, and recently, when our son reported that his 
teachers complimented him and told him how good he was at a given task, we 
discovered that he'd lied. Indeed, he had not done the task properly and far 
from being complimented, he had been kept after class because of his disruptive 
behavior. -- M.P. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR M.P.: I don't believe in "severe" punishment for a 6-year-old and 
certainly not for lying. What is important for parents and teachers to explore 
is why the youngster felt it necessary to lie. I suspect he may be developing a 
habit of lying because of his fear of punishment. 
</P>
<P>
When a 6-year-old lies, intelligent understanding is needed. It's fairly 
obvious that your son wants his teachers to compliment him, to tell him what a 
good boy he is and to reassure him that he's worthwhile and capable of doing 
the tasks required. Most children want desperately to please parents and 
teachers. They like and need praise. 
</P>
<P>
If the only time a child gets the attention of his parents is when he 
misbehaves, then he may deliberately do naughty things in order to draw 
attention to himself. 
</P>
<P>
Why not try to arrange a conference with your son's teacher to try to find out 
what she feels your son needs? When a child consistently lies about his 
performance at school, he may need some professional counseling. This may be a 
cry for help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
