<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SAN JOAQUIN VALLEY; 
</P>
<P>
FOG HAMPERS TRAVEL, TRIGGERS PILEUPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dense fog shrouded the central San Joaquin Valley, closing airports, delaying 
and canceling school bus runs and, California Highway Patrol officers reported, 
causing several major chain-reaction pileups. One of the worst involved 12 to 
14 cars, pickups and truck-trailer rigs on California 41 near Fresno. No deaths 
were reported, but there were several major injuries, officers said. There also 
were chain-reaction pileups in Tulare and near Selma, but no major injuries 
were reported. The CHP said another traffic hazard was created northeast of 
Fresno when about 150 cows wandered onto a road after escaping from a nearby 
pasture. It took officers several hours to round up the cattle in the fog. 
Airports around the valley were fogged in until nearly noon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
