<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH SALUTES NATION ON HOLIDAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush on Monday wished the nation a joyous Hanukkah and a Merry 
Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
To Jews, who begin celebrating the eight days of Hanukkah at sundown Friday, 
Bush recalled that the holiday commemorates a great victory won by the Jewish 
Maccabees in their struggle for religious freedom. 
</P>
<P>
"This year, as Jews around the world pause to observe this festival, all of us 
can share in the joy of those people who are just beginning to enjoy success in 
their own struggle for freedom and self-determination," Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
He told Christians that the promise of the first Christmas continues to give a 
sense of peace and purpose. 
</P>
<P>
"It is daily acts of goodness and generosity, performed time and time again 
throughout the year, that hold the true meaning of this holy season," Bush 
said. 
</P>
