<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
PERSIAN GULF; 
</P>
<P>
ARAB SUMMIT PUTS FOCUS ON IRAN, OIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Persian Gulf Arab leaders began a four-day summit in Muscat, Oman, to debate 
how to deal with Iran after its war with Iraq and to discuss the possibility of 
starting an Arab Common Market to exploit higher oil prices. Omani leader 
Sultan Kaboos ibn Said, host of the 10th meeting of the six-member Gulf 
Cooperation Council, called for changes in the gulf states to better meet 
popular demands at a time of democratic changes in Eastern Europe. Other items 
on the agenda are expected to include the Palestinian uprising in the 
Israeli-occupied territories and the continuing crisis in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
