<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
'REAL' EARNINGS SLIP 0.7% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The real average weekly earnings of American workers, after adjusting for 
inflation and seasonal factors, fell 0.7% in November, the Labor Department 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
It said October real average earnings were unchanged after earlier figures, 
which had shown a 0.6% gain, were revised. 
</P>
<P>
November real average earnings were down 1.5% from the same month a year ago, 
the department said. 
</P>
<P>
The November decline reflected a 0.1% fall in average hourly earnings, a 0.3% 
drop in average weekly hours and a 0.3% rise in the consumer price index for 
urban wage earners and clerical workers, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices rose 0.4% in November after a 0.5% October gain, with higher 
food and housing costs accounting for much of last month's advance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
